Solution Explanation

Unfortunately, as written, the inequality  
\[
\max\Bigl\{
  \frac{x_{1}}{1 + x_{1}},
  \frac{x_{2}}{1 + x_{1} + x_{2}},
  \;\dots,\;
  \frac{x_{n}}{1 + x_{1} + x_{2} + \cdots + x_{n}}
\Bigr\}
\;\ge\;
1 - 2^{-n}
\]
is not correct once \(n \ge 2\).  In fact, one can disprove it by a simple counterexample for \(n = 2\).  

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1) Counterexample for n = 2
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Let \(n = 2\) and take 
\[
x_{1} = 1,
\quad
x_{2} = 0.
\]
Then \(x_{1} + x_{2} = 1\), so the condition \(x_{1} + x_{2} = 1\) is satisfied.  Now look at the two fractions in question:

• The first fraction is  
  \[
  \frac{x_{1}}{1 + x_{1}}
  \;=\;
  \frac{1}{1 + 1}
  \;=\;
  \frac{1}{2}.
  \]

• The second fraction is
  \[
  \frac{x_{2}}{1 + x_{1} + x_{2}}
  \;=\;
  \frac{0}{1 + 1 + 0}
  \;=\;
  0.
  \]

Hence
\[
\max\Bigl\{
  \tfrac{1}{2},\, 0
\Bigr\}
\;=\;
\tfrac{1}{2}.
\]
But for \(n = 2\), the right‐hand side of the claimed inequality is \(1 - 2^{-2} = 1 - \tfrac14 = \tfrac34.\)

Thus
\[
\max\!\Bigl\{
  \tfrac{x_{1}}{1 + x_{1}},
  \tfrac{x_{2}}{1 + x_{1} + x_{2}}
\Bigr\}
\;=\;
\tfrac12
\;<\;
\tfrac34
\;=\;
1 - 2^{-2}.
\]
This violates the proposed inequality, showing that it cannot hold for \(n=2\).  In fact, by trying other values for \(x_1, x_2\) (always with \(x_1 + x_2 = 1\)) one finds that the maximum of those two fractions is never as large as \(3/4.\)

Since the statement already fails for \(n=2\), it is false in general for \(n \ge 2.\)

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2) What goes wrong for larger n?
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Once one sees it fail for \(n=2\), any higher \(n\ge 2\) can be truncated to an \(n=2\) situation (by letting the extra \(x_3,x_4,\dots\) be zero).  The same counterexample structure shows there is no way to repair the statement “for all \(n\ge 1\).”  

Indeed, picking \(x_1 = 1\) and all other \(x_2 = x_3 = \dots = x_n = 0\) gives  
\[
\frac{x_1}{1 + x_1} \;=\; \frac{1}{2},
\quad
\text{and all other terms } = 0,
\]
so 
\(\max\{\dots\} = 1/2\).  
But \(1/2\) is less than \(1 - 2^{-n}\) as soon as \(n \ge 2\).  

Hence the purported inequality is simply not true for \(n\ge 2.\)

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Conclusion
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The correct conclusion is that the inequality  
\[
\max\Bigl\{
  \frac{x_{1}}{1 + x_{1}},
  \frac{x_{2}}{1 + x_{1} + x_{2}},
  \dots,
  \frac{x_{n}}{1 + x_{1} + \cdots + x_{n}}
\Bigr\}
\;\ge\;
1 - 2^{-n}
\]
fails for every \(n\ge 2\).  A concrete counterexample for \(n=2\) (and hence for all larger \(n\) as well) is simply to take \(x_1=1\) and all other \(x_i=0\), which forces the left‐hand‐side to be \(\tfrac12\) but the right‐hand‐side is \(\tfrac34\).
